nsights into the interactive roots of literary creativity, Shvabrin’s interpretative chronicle of Nabokov’s involvement with translation shows how his "dialogic encounters" with others in the medium of translation left "verbal vestiges" on his creations. Refusing to regard translation as a form of individual expression, Nabokov translated to communicate with his interlocutors whose words and images continue to reverberate throughout his allusion-rich texts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Modern / 20th Century .2bisacsh  aLolita.  aMikhail Bakhtin.  aVladimir Nabokov.  adialogic encounters.  adialogue.  ahistory of translation.  aliteralism.  aliterary theory.  aliterature.  atranslation.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065206240uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148751639040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487516390423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487516390.jpg  a978-3-11-065206-2  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles